DATA CLOUD
Vector Search

When you create vector embeddings in Data Cloud, they are added to the search index. You can perform vector search queries from apps such as Prompt Builder, Einstein Copilot, or Tableau.

REQUIRED EDITIONS
Available in: All Editions supported by Data Cloud. See Data Cloud edition availability
Supported File Formats for Vector Search

Data Cloud supports these file formats for search index configurations.

HTML
TXT
PDF 100 MB

For limits and guidelines related to supported file types, see Data Cloud Limits and Guidelines.

Supported CRM Data Types for Vector Search

You can ingest these data types into Data Cloud, map them to the TEXT data type, and enable vector search for them.

Universal Data Dictionary (UDD) types:
Text
Multiline text
Multiline text > 255
HTML Multiline Text
String Plus CLOB: For fields that contain values up to 131 KB
HTML String Plus CLOB: For fields that contain values up to 131 KB
Custom field types:
Text
Text area
Text Area (Long): For fields that contain values up to 131 KB
Text Area (Rich): For fields that contain values up to 131 KB
Supported Embedding Models

Data Cloud supports these embedding models.

E5-Large V2
Multilingual E5-Large (Not supported for Hybrid Search)

Learn more about these models from the Hugging Face documentation.

Create Vector Search Index Configurations
When you create a vector search index configuration for a data model object, Data Cloud breaks up the referenced data into semantically related chunks and generates searchable vectors. These vectors can then be used to find semantically similar items.
Add a Search Index Configuration to a Data Kit
Add search index configurations to a data kit to share functionality across users and environments.
Create a Search Index Configuration from a Data Kit
After you have deployed your data kit in Data Cloud, you can create a new search index configuration from a index it contains.
Run Vector Searches Using Query API
Use Query API to run vector searches in Data Cloud. Use these examples as starting points.
Retrieving Content with Vector Search
With vector search and Einstein Copilot queries, you can capture queries, search across structured and unstructured data sources, and receive summarized responses that improve efficiency and accuracy.
Enhancing Data Analysis with Vector Search in Tableau
Find and analyze data based on meanings, not just keywords, by using vector search in a Tableau query. Vector search broadens the scope of data exploration as well as enhances the accuracy and relevance of the insights by identifying semantic similarities rather than relying solely on exact keyword matches.
